Daily menu of an obese child: no breakfast and sausage dinner
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have overweight problems, where overweight affects 9 per cent of the school population and obesity at 5 per cent.
Obese children come mostly from families with a non-healthy lifestyle, according to current research.
It is again demonstrated the importance of the environment where it grows for a healthy development of the person, as well as the models that serve as a reference.
At the table, obsessed children feed, for example, on sausages at least twice as often as children from families with normal weight.
For dinner, more than 19 percent of obese people had had chips dined the day before the test, which is linked to the "obesity is not a coincidence" prevention program.
In the families of overweight children there is no habit of playing sports, which applies to most current families, where only 15 per cent of children responded that their parents, at least once a week, find time for physical exercise.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was carried out at the end of last school year and almost 900 children from Basic Education from all over the world participated in the same period.
It was already the second edition of the "Obesity of No Chance" program, supported by the General Health Insurance Company and Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 children have participated in the project from the 4th to the 8th year.
A proper diet and a lot of family exercise are determining factors, which significantly reduce the number of overweight and even obesity children.
"Only half of the children surveyed have responded that they have five meals a day according to the regime: breakfast, lunch, lunch, snack and dinner, which is one of the basic conditions for a healthy diet," says one of the survey's results.
No breakfast but with sausage for dinner
Specialists warn that, in a healthy development, details are also important, which also count, such as having a fixed hour for family breakfast.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23% of school families eat breakfast at the same time.
In most families, each one has breakfast alone.
But the worst part was to discover that 10 per cent of households don't eat breakfast.
Breakfast is, however, the basis of a correct daily diet.
The study shows that in families of obese children, the insane chips are consumed much more frequently.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drink sweet soft drinks (70%) daily.
As a rule, more than 40 per cent of the children surveyed play sports, however, among their parents this result is less than half, only 15 per cent.
Fasting your diet
The next phase of the study enabled the chosen boys (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own diets from all possible offers according to their tastes and opinions.
"The food preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15, from the point of view of healthy eating, are far from ideal."
Among his favorite foods are pasta, meat and sweets
"The popularity of sweet soft drinks is especially alarming," the study's final report warns.
As a main meal, the pasta takes the palm and follows the bird meat closely.
Practically, children always reject legume and taste for fish and vegetables is very low.
Change to healthy habits
At the same time, the study shows that children are willing to change their eating habits if they receive the right information.
"In the control group of the study participants, who filled out the questionnaire after finishing the prevention program "obesity is not a coincidence," there was in many cases a major change in favor of the principles of healthy eating," the study results note.
Attention, for example, is what sugars are about sweet soft drinks, where many children would start to prefer normal and running water.
Children would also choose more frequently in the questionnaire bird meat and fish for the main food and restrict the consumption of sweet food and flour derivatives.
