In Need for Speed: The Run competes across America.
Review
A trip, in principle carefree, is complicated by a series of improper neglects of a routine trip during tomorrow's shift.
To some extent, expectations were met, but this is of no use, if, in reality, nothing was intended to be done extraordinary.
The new installment, to which The Run is added to the title, aroused high expectations already before its premiere.
He promised to give new air to the old Need for Speed racing saga and, as a result of what was shown, appears as a game that should not end up being a genre of action again.
We are also curious to know what the scenes would look like, where the main character descends from the car and walks on his own foot.
As is often the case in the NFS series, the results do not vary much from what we expected.
There are races that can be taken for granted, but in the total computation points are lost due to absurd failures, which have already appeared in the series for years.
In reality they cannot be called errors, but rather it is about the incomprehensible rest of programmers.
The adventure starts very well.
You're introduced to a story, whose protagonist, Jack, has certain personal problems; to solve them, he is offered to participate in an illegal career throughout America.
You sit behind the wheel on the west coast in San Francisco, and your mission is to get the first to New York.
The idea is to offer something interesting.
The route is divided into ten stages and then into more than fifty races.
It follows that each race takes place on a different route and the stages are located in different environments, which are quite diverse and interesting.
That way, you don't even remotely have the feeling that the game always offers the same.
Some of the environments are even pleasant to the eye, although the technical level of the graph is equivalent to that of previous deliveries of the series.
So it's nothing from the other world.
But the walk through the desert, the fall landscape or the high snow-covered mountains produce a very pleasant visual effect.
In addition, racing is diversified from time to time by an atypical element.
So, for example, in the desert you find a sandstorm that decreases visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains you have to be careful not to bury you an avalanche.
According to that, each of the races is very well developed.
There's only a couple of models, but that's enough.
For a moment, try to overtake a number of required rivals (normal in a classic race), then try to buy time (classic timed) and then expect a duel against a single opponent.
In the midst of all this sometimes the police appear, who only make things even more difficult.
The novelty is the landscapes outside the car.
Interactive animations are presented when Jack, in most cases, has to escape someone and you have to help him, always pressing the button right at the right time.
Nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are plenty of fewer landscapes in the game than you would expect (in particular there are only three).
But the end result is positive, because this element does not become annoying and, in the context already mentioned, it is one of the elements that make the game more interesting.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of previous episodes.
That means that today it is no longer a big deal, but you can't say it's bad.
If you're looking for a realistic simulation, you can search elsewhere.
But a race conceived with quite an action is good for this driving style, although we can find something better between the competition games.
So far, everything in order.
But the problems arise after a certain time.
Unlike the correctness of driving models, the same is no longer the case with collisions.
Of such games you can't expect him to recreate complicated deformations and collisions, but in fact before a blow to any object, you can't predict how your car will react, so it's not all in order.
It is typical that, by making a very tight advance or circulating the car with normal traffic, there are only slight frictions, but in other almost identical situations, your car ends up doing uncontrolled pirouettes.
Or it even ends up completely destroyed.
Thanks to the reset system, no big problems arise, but it can put you in a bad mood.
The resets are programmed in such a way that, when you suffer an accident or you get off the track, the game returns you to the last rescue point on the track.
However, in each race only five resets are available.
If you consume them all, you have to restart the race from the beginning.
So it's just a help in case something doesn't go well, but it's not very reliable.
Sometimes, neither the reset helps, it only helps to learn the given stage of memory.
A great disadvantage of the game is that the same facts are repeated in different places.
In some curves, for example, you have to enter in a specific way; otherwise, they are impossible to take.
Other times you find yourself somewhere "civilian" vehicles always with the same configuration, even if you are the first, fifth or arrive five minutes before or after.
This makes you rage especially in situations, when you see that two cars that go to meet in opposite directions, your opponent advances without problems, but when you arrive, you must turn or brake.
It's the same when you get there, because it's programmed that the "surprise" will always happen under your nose.
Opponents also have one more advantage.
Throughout the game you will arrive at places where, without taking into account the moment, the same opponent will always advance you in the same place.
This also happens at the end of the game, on a long bridge, which is even more shocking.
Your opponent must come before you are, whatever price.
When he goes in front of you, it makes it difficult for you to see the cars coming from the front, so at first you can make the car ackle.
You can understand the idea of creating a game with maximum doses of suspense and adrenaline, but the execution is so apparent that you are probably disappointed right away.
And it's a shame, because even if the model of the trip is simple, the game is fun and with action, so it's often not possible to follow in detail what happens or where.
And it really doesn't matter, if the credit is taken up the idea with fifty exclusive tracks or the classification in the race so that boredom doesn't fit, or anything else.
An unusual idea is the change of cars during racing.
You have to be attentive to the gasoline dispensers next to the road, because right there you have to change cars, although in the vast majority of cases you will suffice what you have.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports are suitable for urban areas, American strong cars for straight highways and exotic supersports for technical driving, for example, on curved mountain roads.
In addition, the main narrative thread also appears a thread of parallel challenges, that is, there are races in concrete places that you will know about the stories.
Here you will get not only medals, but also points of experience for your profile, which serves both challenges and stories.
Upon reaching the upper level, the driver opens several possibilities, starting with the car and ending with funds for the profile.
At the same time, there is an online Autolog feature, which compares your results with those of other players and develops other community functions.
One of the hardest elements to understand is how the last race in history is made.
With the car you arrive to the subway tunnel (pass), where you start running in the dark on the tracks (pass).
The speedometer marks you between 150 and 200 km/h (pass) and suddenly the subway convoy comes from behind you and you are just ahead.
In the newsroom we will surely have a discussion about this for several days, about whether during the game's programming none thought even a little or if the authors really take us for a buzz of fools.
The technical part of the game is nothing extraordinary, but at least the general visual effects result in most cases pleasant, sometimes even superb.
It is too bad that, in the most tense moments, image quality is reduced and sometimes in a serious way.
This mainly affects accidents involving many participants, when the continuous image quality is no longer valid.
The audio is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of tastes.
In order for most of the youth group to be liking, the soundtrack belongs to the category "each of his father and his mother," but it can be assumed that no one would buy the game just for his music.
The final sensation of Need for Speed: The Run is therefore quite confusing.
If the game avoided absolutely silly mistakes, we would have trouble claiming The Run is the best NFS game of recent years.
It gives the feeling that the game is not done.
The fun is assured, but prepare because the mistakes will hit you in the eyes with the strength of airport reflectors.
The choirs of Carolina University will participate in the concert "Eudiantes de Tertillo."
The joint celebration of International Students' Day and the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution as a musical experience will take place for the third time at the Festa Academica festival.
During it, twenty corals from high schools and university centres will be presented.
The festival revolves around two concerts on November 17.
"Carlian University has a high participation in the festival."
Among the current choirs are the choral of the Faculty of Pedagogy and the Faculty of Humanities, in the committee of the festival is the rector Václav Hampl," said the head of the organization, Jakub Ealoun.
The summit of the entire festival is the free entrance for all audiences to the concert of the high school choirs, which will be held on March 17 at 2 p.m. in front of the National Technical Libraría in Dejvice.
The program has the participation of Czech jazzist Karel Roika and his Celebration Jazz Mass.
In the evening, the concert "Esters of Velvet" will be held at the venues of the Municipal House in Vynohrady, in which university choirs will participate, including the Carolina Uninversity choir.
The Academic Festa aims not only to celebrate the International Students' Day with dignity and to remember the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present the public with choral music at the highest level and to promote collaborative creation among young people.
The main organizer is the Czech Union of Corals in collaboration with the Jan Kepler Secondary Institute.
All the events were supported by the mayor of Prague, Bohuslav Svoboda, and the rector of Carolina University, Václav Hampl.
The Festival will run from 16 to 20 November between Prague and Pardubice.
The calendar offers, in addition to the celebratory concerts, a whole series of musical events, improvised student shows and morning concerts.
More information can be found on the festival page www.festaacademica.cz
