How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia at the time: Eedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies at the time sold in most cases trips only to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists went on holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it could be traveled to Yugoslavia, however, the Yugoslav regime then bowed to the west and the trips of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even through the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise the individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West at the time, but one had to queue with a sleeping bag and spend the whole night, or have "good acquaintances" at the agency.
Still, it wasn't all won.
The so-called "promise of change" that was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable people," who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cabins and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The way Czechs travel has suffered from a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was the no longer to spend the holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million holiday trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, the fact that Croatia, until 1989 could not be traveled freely, because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
In the early 1990s, visa waiver was imposed to travel to Western European neighbouring states, prompting a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, weren't fed up with the tours to the West, everyone wanted to see him for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris the groups of Czechs slept in the parks in tents, as our income at the time did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical characteristic of Czechs at the time was to take with them food (conserves, sausages, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living was also increasing and with it the average wages, which around 1997 led to an increase in demand for travel.
With the increase in travel demand, agencies began, from 1997 regularly to prepare for travel using charter flight connections, which made travel prices incredibly lower compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for the volume of passengers.
By the late 1990s, Czechs already travel visaless to almost every developed country except the US, which further simplified our journeys.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened as early as 2000, when it was organized, thanks to enormous demand, the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights have departed every year with Czech tourists to distant and hot countries. This winter it will already fly directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by about 100,000 Czechs per year.
Another interesting moment of this time, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, arrived in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US eliminated visas for Czech tourists, making our country more developed among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3 per cent) and for the first time in their history, more than 15,000 Czech kronor per head, have spent on foreign trips, including expenses at the stay site.
