On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to carrying out a massacre in Norway in July, which left 77 dead, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of the time he preceded his attack on his computer, chatting to some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After this summer's tragedy, investigators wanted to know more about these people.
But how do you find them?
Easy - you just have to go on Facebook.
"We realized it wasn't that hard to get to them," says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European digital populism by the British think tank DEMOS.
Facebook's personal information cache is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic characteristics with scientific accuracy - the way sellers have been using for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then ran ads, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey asking about their educational level, attitudes towards violence and optimism about their own future.
Upon arriving via Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - all without leaving the office.
"It's a whole new way to do an investigation," Bartlett says.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, male and angry about immigration.
However, in a kind of twist, "those who combine their activism online with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind the computer screen."
DEMOS's work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming an important new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything from health problems to social trends as expressed in "Like," messages on walls and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating a surge in research, driving the number of academic jobs with the site's name on the title to almost 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn't get close to with a folder on the street.
"Before, when you were trying to survey people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to go through the game, and they would never allow you access," Bartlett says.
"Facebook eliminates all that - you go to them directly."
Others say the site could provide a way to identify and address health-social problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno, of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and her colleagues, found that college students who talked about their drunkenness feats on Facebook had a significantly higher risk of having drinking problems than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that students' peers, such as residential counselors, could control the site and intervene to help a student posting too many status updates with their drunkenness.
"You can't treat a problem if you can't diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, Moreno's co-author and director of the Center for Health, Behavior and Child Development at the Seattle Children's Research Institute, the Washington Post said.
"We have found a way to identify children at risk who would otherwise not be diagnosed."
Facebook is also constantly "puncturing" its own population to get data.
The site's Data Team has produced statistics on the status of the relationship and Valentine's Day, the expectation of voter turnout in the middle of the 2010 legislative period, and a National Happiness Index (mainly using the information that can be accessed - long-standing digital freedom advocates who argue that the site should make its large amount of data available to others for research).
However, Facebook users know the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - the sacrifice for being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is to allow the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don't even know?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, online is a free bar for everyone.
"I don't think many of the users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be examining their profiles," Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, says of a 2006 study he conducted with Facebook's public walls of students.
"In what he was concerned about, it was only between them and their friends."
Then there's the question of methodology.
Even offline, there's no guarantee that a research topic is being completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know that some of the information on a user's profile and wall messages are true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do off Facebook are two completely different things," Selwyn says.
That's why, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn believes that a paper and pen are still the best investigative tools anyone can use.
"There's no substitute for getting into the real world and talking to real people," he says.
