7 Lessons from Steve Jobs' Lost Interview, shown in a theater this week
After Steve Jobs' death on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford - distinguishing the genius from technology as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find more revealing, in an interview with recently rediscovered Jobs that has been dusted as a preview of a series of special screenings in major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about the trade processes and workflows of products.
He was certainly a self-recognised designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organiser and a junkie of the flow charts - a man who believed many executives suffered "a disease that consists of thinking that a great idea is 90 per cent of the job... [but] there's a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds on the dawn of the personal computer, and sat for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At the time it had been just 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, waiting for popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of Cringely's interview was used in Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during his transport.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full copy of VHS was discovered in the director's garage.
This slightly reissued archive material is the basis of Steve Jobs: The lost, 68-minute interview that hits Landmark cinemas on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known for hating in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between the questions and the answers - from 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, looking for precision.
There are also moments when Jobs' perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient due to Cringely's questions, pushing him to go faster towards the most important issues or arguments.
Filmed before the Pixar era, iPod or iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic about The Lost Interview, when Jobs assesses what other companies do well and wrong, and offers their own vision for the future of computing.
It's one thing to read posthumous assessments of Jobs' career, but there's something raw and inspiring about Jobs that we see here, the long-awaited dreamer on the brink of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, it was and did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences from The Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"Throughout the years in the business, I always asked, "Why do you do things?" and the answers they give you invariably are: "Oh, that's just the way it's done."
Nobody knows why he does what he does, in business nobody thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs takes his efforts to simplify Apple's accounting into detail.
Baffled by the way in which the costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was made to the eye of good cube, and then adjusted with a "variable" - he developed an automated factory that ensured they could determine commercial costs in detail.
On the joke to the Pope:
Jobs narrates the "Blue Case" he himself built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make free long-distance calls.
It has been widely written about the device, but Jobs' euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a pay phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
"We were wrapping things around the world a half dozen times and screaming through the pay-day phone and going back a minute later to the pay phone at the door next door," Jobs says with a chuckle.
"We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world."
We both didn't know much, but we could build a small thing that could control a giant thing - it was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would ever have existed without it.
Jobs goes on to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost abandoned, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and asking to speak to the Pope, while doing his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the US diplomat, the two burst into laughter just before the Pope himself was woken to go answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and phone sale with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, on the hunt for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he searched Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
'That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I'd seen at that age and formed my vision of what a company was and how well they treated its employees.'
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made."
It was as big as a suitcase, I had a small cathode tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I'd get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste my time with that machine and write programs for it.
On improvising innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the go.
Soon in his career, as he dedicated himself to selling a handful of base plates, a customer asked if he could assemble the entire equipment.
Working on only 30 days of credit, I had to figure out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember having dramatic arguments ... they were yelling at me that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got tired and went away and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
On big companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple's revival, Jobs prophetically anticipated the way many industry leaders would stumble on his vision, and lose control of their market share.
"Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you do better photocopiers and printers, and what?"
You have a monopoly on market share, so the company is no more successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it is these kinds of people who end up running companies and people in charge of products are expelled from the decision-making forum.
The genius of the products that led to this monopoly position is rostruted because of people who do not have the notion of good products vs bad products - the knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They took the defeat of victory.
On innovation as an artistic expression:
"There's a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product ... as the big idea evolves, changes and grows."
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to do - some things you can't do to do electrons, the glass makes them, the robots do, the factories make them.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
In the end it all comes down to taste - it comes down to trying to expose yourself to the best a team of humans has done, and then try to adapt those things you're doing.
Picasso said good artists copy, the great artists steal.
We've never been ashamed about stealing big ideas.
What made Macintosh great was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who were casually the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn't for computing, I could be doing wonderful things in other fields.
