How to detect a lie
A look at the most recent headlines tells us how serious and ubiquitous the deception and lies in daily life are.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging sexual harassment allegations with several women; each side accuses of lying to the other.
Administrators at Pennsylvania State University have been charged with perjury for allegedly concealing reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was "picked" with an open microphone claiming US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitor Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself with his denials quickly refuted by the irrefutable test.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign funding offences related to the cover-up of an extramarital relationship.
And, again, no one who lived it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton as he lied during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends on traps in school and university exams are widespread.
There have been cases where teachers have given exam responses to students in order to be better seen in their performance evaluations.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite are sending the message that lying and deceiving are acceptable.
How much deceit are we found?
On any given day, studies show you can lie anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That's sure, a lot of those lies are godly lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Detecting lies, or "the location of lies," is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have you," the detection of deception is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the last six decades in prestigious universities that carried out in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about the lie have been refuted.
Liars do look into the eyes.
They don't always stutter, babble, blush or restless.
It cannot be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, the formation of questions and the times.
I spent several years probing scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that detecting deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, or negotiating management.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, making them feel comfortable, managing their own emotions and feeling intuitively how others perceive them.
We know from the research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more "self-oriented lies," while women say more "targeted" lies -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people less often lie to their partners than people who are not married (but the lies they often say tend to be "huge").
We also know that if you are perceived as a baddoer, others will feel less guilty in lying to you.
How do you know if anyone is lying?
First, observe the subject's usual behavior.
This is called "creating a baseline."
Helps provide benchmarks to measure changes later.
Observe the subject's posture, laughter and vocal feature.
You'd better know if someone normally hits the footy all the time so they don't make unfair accusations when they see their feet punching in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for deceptive, verbal and nonverbal behavioral groups.
Consider these behavioral groups as alarm signals, not as proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the upper body by trying to remember their story, can point their feet at the door, lean towards an exit, change their posture significantly or display a "post-interview relief" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and posture change once all the difficult questions are over.
Questioners often falsely show that the interview is over only to seek that post-interview relief.
He also pays attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson screwed up to the bottom and used the time spent while claiming his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
People who cheat can also use a distance language: "I didn't have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when they answer a difficult question: "Well... to tell you the truth... to what I know... to me.."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning sign.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to discover the deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone's chances to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
