Climate adversity slowed the economy
During the first year of administration of Mario López Valdez, unemployment and informality have increased in Sinaloa, foreign investment has fallen and the economy contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, this is the first year of the government of Mario López Valdez, self-styled of change, which generated high expectations regarding the advances in the economy, but given the climatic adversity of the beginning of the year, there is no growth, but there is no deterioration in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, in addition to causing millions of losses for the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state economy to grow, caused a contraction of overall economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, justified mainly by the historic fall of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of frost effects, issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there were damage to 52,835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 per cent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 per cent had partial damage, the main sinister crops were those of vegetables, corn and chickpeas.
The fall in economic activity has generated, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the state unemployment rate during the first three quarters of the year accelerated growth, since from January to March 55,053 Sinaloans were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the economically active population, for the second quarter the rate rose to 5.28 percent, and between July and September the average continued to increase to 6.19 percent, a rate that in the number of people.more than 74,000 unemployed Sinaloans, an increase from the first semester of 18,969.
Reduced liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that have been carried out from public policy.
"What is being seen is an increase in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to the effects of a resource restriction by the legislation that was passed in Congress to combat money laundering, already for people who grab dollars illegally it is not easy for them to work, invest them and use them in something," he said.
Immigration arrested
López Cervantes pointed out that there is also a demographic factor in the increase in unemployment.
"The number of people leaving the state in search of work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, first because of the difficulties in entering, and second because entering they already have many difficulties in finding work, those people are staying and are demanding sources of work here in the state, which causes unemployment to rise," he said.
Informality
The analysis of the Sinaloan labour market is aggravated by considering the high level of informality that predominates among working conditions, according to the INEGI, 60.38 percent of the employed population in the state works without being quoted as a worker before any social security institution.
In addition to unemployment and informality, another of the state's labor lags are low wages, the entity has the lowest wages in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Social Security Institute and the Ministry of Labour and Social Security.
The average monthly income of Sinaloan workers was, until September, 5, 352 pesos, well below the national average, located at 7, 375 pesos.
Attraction of FDI
In addition to the fall in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, during 2011 there was the largest decrease in foreign direct investment in the last 10 years, according to the Ministry of Economy from January to June of state FDI totaled 630,697 dollars, representing a fall of 87.74 percent from the 5 million 143 thousand 312 dollars recorded during the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the Secretariat for Economic Development of the State Government counts a total investment of 17 280 million pesos in the year, which occurred mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
Debt
Faced with the scenario of economic contraction, the state government requested in July the state congress to approve a credit for 3 billion pesos, which would be destined for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, in order to reactivate the economy, the approval of the local congress was in the amount of 2.6 billion pesos, and until November they have not observed the benefits of indebtedness in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the business sector, Mario López Valdés' first year of government shows a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that during 2011 he lacked the harmonization of wills of the different sectors, including the state government itself.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we have to work hard to recover the ground we lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble our efforts, we have to align everyone's efforts and above all the good progress already synchronized of this new government team, we hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Economic contentment
Loredo López said that events such as the frosts of the beginning of the year stopped the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, including frosts, one of the main effects has been a sluggish economy that does not turn around fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we are closing well below the expectations we had," he said.
Redefine vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Employers' Confederation of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, said that it is necessary to prosecute the state towards productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that work has been done, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program in which the vocation and economic direction of the state is redefined, because it is important that the full potential of the material and human resource that Sinaloa has be detonated," he said.
Work to do
The president of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better channels the government's efforts.
"Overall I would say that the government has been striving to deliver good results in various areas, in terms of economic development there is some progress in the area but it is important that a long-term programme be developed," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in its way of conducting public policy.
"There are elements that make it possible to say that the government is being more inclusive, I can say what I can say is that there is work done and I think the government is aware that there is work to be done," he said.
