The possibility of the count "vote per vote" is a reality in terms of this year's electoral process in Michoacán, where according to the data released by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6,000 74 total minutes.
In this regard, the president of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Angeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, just on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines in order to harmonize local standards with federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not approve his Political Constitution or State Electoral Code or his Electoral Justice Act, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the end of the legal period so that they could enter into force in the present electoral process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication within the time limits provided for in the Law on the Official State Newspaper, arguing that he had some objections.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional dispute promoted by the local legislature and described as "invalid and illegal" the state president's vote on constitutional reforms, since he has no right to "sanction or veto them."
Interviewed about the possibility of the "vote by vote," María de los Angeles Llanderal explained that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the IEM, it will be possible to carry out partial and total counts of the vote by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial count of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may occur in cases that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of scrutiny and counting in the record of the box or does not work in the possession of the president of the box; or, when there are obvious errors or alterations of the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the vote received in all the poll boxes may be carried out when there is an indication that the difference between the alleged candidate winner of the election in question and the one who has obtained the second place in the vote is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is the express request of the representative of the party and/or coalition that nominated the second of the candidates indicated.
The total count of the vote may also be carried out if at the end of the ordinary computation it is established that the difference between the allegedly winning candidate and the candidate second is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is the express request of the representative of the political party whose candidate was second, in which case the electoral packages that have been partially recounted will be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that in this situation is the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, although without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
