The appointed Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet on Wednesday with Italy's president to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and has endangered the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet Wednesday with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he can form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he will present the president with the outcome of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say that he will be able to form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
The "framework is now well delineated," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than normal, as Italy battles a political and financial crisis that has driven the costs of its debt to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a harsh austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain beacons confidence in Italy.
Underscoring pressure on Monti to rush, market volatility put the yield on 10-year BTP Italian bonds above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be rescued.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian boss Confindustria, told the press after meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government very much."
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to emerge from this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success were significantly driven by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, who was forced by the crisis to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told the press.
The support of the PDL, Italy's largest party, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the technocrat majority government that Monti is forming.
Parliamentary support
Monti's new government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what is likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blocking or delay in their efforts could lead to a further and devastating attack by financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by warning that a failure of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began its consultations on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as with youth and women's organizations.
He will end his round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, which has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty over whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Rescuing Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 trillion euros, would be too much for the eurozone's current financial defences.
Monti has said his government should last until the next election, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms before the elections are brought forward.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist it should be made up of technicians alone, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources pointed out that mutual mistrust and disagreements between the parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
