Since November, Mexico has presided over the G20, a group made up of the most powerful emerging and developed countries in the world, and has been in force with the South American country, since January of this year, an agreement to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has tried to speed up the implementation of tax-exchange agreements in order to emerge from the "grey list" of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), made up of countries that did not implement all international standards of fiscal cooperation.
At the trade level, Mexico and Uruguay have in force since 2004 a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) that has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
