This was the work of the caleño who identified Alfonso Cano's body.
A lophoscopist from Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano."
The work of these officials is key.
On November 4, a lophoscopist from the CTI of Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the identity of the top head of the Farc: "Alfonso Cano," through the cross-check of his fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists who work in the section of the CTI, that week it was the turn of "availability" to Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the area of judicial investigation for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in municipalities of Chocó, where he often had to enter the jungle for more than five days to get to the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000, he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after taking the corresponding courses, specialized in lophosphorytry, which is the study of the friction skin, that is, the palms of the hands and feet.
The week of the operation against aliases Alfonso Cano to Eliazar was warned to wear minimum clothes for three days.
Something big expected.
On Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies and that it was suspected that one of them was the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so they asked him to carry Guillermo León Sáenz's decadactilar card (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigation team at the site where the body was located he did not recognize him because of his physical appearance, as it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He was without a beard, dressed as a peasant in the area, without glasses and much thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a transplanter and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse to those of the card.
His eye didn't fail him: it was "Alfonso Cano."
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of confirming to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was the top head of the Farc.
In search of the footprint
For a dactiloscopista de la Sijín de Cali, the recognition made by President Juan Manuel Santos to Eliazar González, at the press conference for the operation against "Cano," is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, without margin for error, that can become key in solving crimes.
Apart from the identification of corpses, the lophoscopists support investigations into crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many criminals have false ballots or do not have papers.
We take the dataset print and search them in the database.
The investigator said that, in a case of theft, it was his turn to remove a piece of wall from a house, because in that place the thief had supported his hand to take out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not appropriate surfaces to get a fingerprint, but in that case we were able to get the footprint of the whole hand and identify the offender, who had participated in different thefts," he recalled.
Footprints can also rule out or reassert suspects in homicide cases.
They recently found a dead man, with bottles of liquor around him.
The investigation found that a relative could be a suspect in the crime and indeed a print on the bottle matched.
Although this does not guarantee that he was the killer, he does put him at the scene of the crime.
A CTI fingerprint explained that in objects "prints are taken out with chemical or physical reagents."
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used to lift them.
After this, the impressions are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," said the CTI expert.
He clarified that not everything is as shown on the TV show CSI.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything that is touched becomes a mark.
However, if it can be used, if the respective cross-commady is done.
The "outraged" challenge authorities in New York
Hundreds of protesters crowded in front of Zuccotti Square to camp.
A large part he served the eviction order and moved to a nearby paruqe.
Members of the Occupy Wall Street movement challenged the New York authorities on Tuesday by trying to enter again, under the protection of a court order, to Manhattan Square from where they were evicted in the early morning and trying to occupy another park in the Big Apple.
Hundreds of protesters crowded in front of Zuccotti Square, where they wanted to access thanks to a court order that allows the "outraged" to camp again on the spot, while another part of the movement responded to the eviction by occupying a park further north of the city, where there have been new arrests.
"Our idea is that, if the court doesn't allow us to camp in the square again, we're going to settle somewhere else and we'll continue the legal battle to get back to Zuccotti, as well as through peaceful sit-ins and demonstrations," said one of the spokesmen for the "Occupy Wall Street" movement, Mark Bray.
Bray detailed that the "outraged" response to the eviction of their camp personally dictated by New York Mayor Michael Bloomberg reached the courts, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting the forced evacuation of the site and allowed protesters to stay camped.
In addition, the "outraged" proceeded to occupy a new park located at the confluence of the central Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland tunnel, which links New York and New Jersey, and owned by the parish of Trinity Church.
At least an hour they managed to take the place, but then the police came and proceeded to arrest some of the protesters, although Bray could not confirm the specific figure, while telling Efe that he saw several journalists who were also handcuffed.
The organization claims that several hundred people had settled at that point, where a delegation of religious leaders has already moved in support of the members of the movement and has tried to mediate with the police.
Meanwhile, Zuccotti Square - which is a privately owned enclosure - is still closed pending the holding of a court hearing scheduled for this same Tuesday in which the legality of the evacuation of this morning must be analyzed.
Some of the protesters displaced there carried and distributed copies of that court order at this time and even handed them over to the officers guarding the square, which caused "some small clashes," said Bray, who denounced that some officers beating the protesters.
The court order prohibits authorities from evicting members of Occupy Wall Street or applying "laws that were published after the occupation began or to ban protesters from accessing the park again with shops or other properties they previously used."
Mayor Bloomberg told the press that, due to this court order, the city had suspended the reopening of the space to the public and the protesters, whom he warned, however, that local laws do not allow them to re-install tents and sleeping bags.
The governor personally defended the eviction carried out in the early morning of Zuccotti Square, an operation in which about 200 arrests were carried out and which was decided because the protesters were "violating the law."
Bloomberg explained that he gave the order to evacuate the square because it was becoming "a place where people would not come to protest, but to violate the laws and, in some cases, to hurt other people," since "some businesses had received threats" and the neighbors fear "for their quality of life."
"The eviction this morning was disgusting and shows that in the background Bloomberg is more interested in preserving the financial interests than those of American workers," added the spokesman for the movement, who accused the mayor of "disrespecting freedom of expression."
"Occupy Wall Street" also indicated that they plan to organize "great actions" for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and unions, to commemorate the two months of the protests, which began on September 17.
