Japan reborn after earthquake
GDP grows by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and puts an end to the spiral of falls that began in March
Since last March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, still convalescent of the devastating earthquake that occurred in a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe that the Japanese country has suffered since World War II.
The Tokyo Government's first estimates put material losses at $300 billion, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, appears to have been mitigated.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, the data of the Gross Domestic Product between July and September served to move the page, definitely: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% in annualized rate.
The one recorded in the second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also represents the highest rate of growth from January to March 2010.
The recovery is explained, in part, by the upsurge in the purchase of machinery to restore areas ravaged by earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1 per cent, compared with a 0.9 per cent decline in capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first setback after six months of uninterrupted rises.
However, the real revulsiveness of the Japanese economy is not based solely on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of crises to strengthen - or rebuild - infrastructure, use the shortcomings to grow from scratch.
Japan has awakened, above all, thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable climbed by 1%, pushed by increased spending on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo has been entrusted to the internal market, when the yen - the Japanese currency - has become one of the "fever values" chosen by investors fleeing the eurozone debt crisis and US forecasts, a privilege that weighs as a slab on the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger currency, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic floating line is determined by the health of large technology groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, blamed its weak results between July and September on the yen's quotation.
While markets continue their siege of the peripheral EU countries, the Yoshihiko Noda government does not lower its guard.
"We must be attentive to the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of Thailand's floods and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said Secretary of State for Economic Policy Motohisa Furukawa yesterday.
And indeed, the outlook is not encouraging.
The Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) said most member countries showed sharper signs of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the turning points in the world economy has shown that the major powers are slowing down.
As it dropped four tenths to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
The euro area, even below the average, which is at level 100, with eight tenths rushing to 99.13 points.
Athens feeds the doubts again
Papadimos says adjustments will be approved, but conservatives will not sign any written commitments
With peripheral risk premiums skyrocketing and uncertainty reinstated in the patches, Greece continues to entangle in the maze leading to the exit of the great European debt crisis.
The feeling that the "consensus" of the new Greek transitional government comes more imposed by Brussels' demands than by a genuine conviction of political forces is beginning to be confirmed with facts.
While the new Prime Minister, Lukas Papadimos, warned yesterday that there is no alternative to structural reforms and that the 100-day period agreed in his appointment may fall short to implement them, the leader of the conservative New Democracy party, Antonis Samaras, said he will not support new austerity measures in any case and reiterated his demand for new elections for the scheduled date, February 19.
"The main task of this government is to implement the decisions of the summit of 26 October," Papadimos said at the opening yesterday of a parliamentary debate that will culminate tomorrow with a vote of confidence to the new Executive.
A package with 24 programmes to boost employment, reform of the civil servants' disciplinary code and new measures against tax evasion will be the first initiatives.
However, Samaras' message does not clear the doubts about her position: "We are committed to helping the transitional government, but we have not committed ourselves to anything else."
The Conservative leader was a step further in his pulse to the EU and the IMF, the agencies that must unlock the 8 billion Athens urgently needs, and made it clear that he will not give his approval to any letter of commitment to comply with the adjustments.
But the European Commission, still echoed by the impact caused by the ordeal of Papandreu's referendum, reiterated yesterday that its demand is firm: it will not unlock aid if the new government and the leaders of the main Greek parties do not sign "a written commitment without ambiguity and as soon as possible."
Economic Affairs spokesman Amadeu Altafaj explained that troika inspectors will return "very soon" to Athens to discuss with the new government "what is needed to pay the sixth tranche" of 8 billion, although there is no definitive date either.
The Greek skewer still has thread for a while.
Doña Sofia: "They are instruments for progress and hope"
The Queen highlights Spain's "preponderant" place in relation to this type of finance
Spain "has reached a global high in the role of Microfinance."
Queen Sofia recalled yesterday that the country has become the second donor of the last two decades to raise this intrusion of cooperation, whose "essence" lies in being an "instrument for social progress, justice and hope for a better future for all humanity, based on trust in the human being."
The Queen inaugurated yesterday the 5th World Microcredit Summit in Valladolid with the conviction that "there is no doubt" that this type of operation is "absolutely indispensable" to achieve the Millennium Goals set by the United Nations with horizon 2015, and, "very especially, in which it aims to reduce by half the volume of people living on incomes below a daily dollar, with which the "threshold of poverty" is fixed.
Spain "continues to work" to expand the network of beneficiaries "to all corners of the planet, and assumes this task with "responsibility," said Doña Sofia, who hoped that the initiatives and contributions that originate at the Summit, which will last until Thursday, "guarantee the creation of new capacities and better opportunities for the poorest, and especially for women," the main beneficiaries of these loans.
There are "many achievements" and "many of the challenges we face."
The Microcredit Summit is proposed not only as a forum for discussion, but also as the platform from which to promote "two basic goals."
Thus, Her Majesty explained that 175 million poor families who have accessed these financial services will be 175 million at the end of 2015 and that 100 million of these households will leave the poverty line at which they are plunged.
The impulse in the conception of microcredit in Spain and the rest of the world "has followed the path begun years ago in a pioneering way" by Muhammad Yunus, highlighted Doña Sofia as an "act of justice and due recognition."
He described the father of this tool as an "admirable idealist in the universal cause of the fight against poverty," whose work he has known for 15 years, when the Queen travelled to Bangladesh to learn about her loan policy on the ground.
This experience was followed a year later by the first World Summit in Washington and other meetings such as those held in Ivory Coast in 1999, Canada 2006, and "in all I have been able to see the continuous evolution," explained His Majesty, whose link with this project yesterday earned him the qualification of the "head of the family" gathered in Valladolid by the "battle of the poor."
Finally, Queen Sofia concluded her speech by encouraging those present to participate in the debate and in the search for solutions to advance the fight against poverty.
"Ethical Imperative"
The Minister of Foreign Affairs, Trinidad Jiménez, warned that solidarity "is an ethical imperative" for every democratic state.
