A committee of experts says euthanasia and assisted suicide should be legalised
Canadians live in denial of death, Royal Society of Canada report says
In the area of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, and not just in cancer cases.
Canadian society lives in denial of death.
In fact, only 9 percent of Canadians are willing to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make arrangements to that effect.
This is one of the findings of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, with the participation of six experts from various fields, including ethics, legal and physician.
This committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code in a way that assisted suicide and euthanasia is allowed, when the patient raises this option and has been tried competent to make the decision.
For starters, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit that compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
Although Canada ranks 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid to deal with the issue of death."
On medication or not, 77 percent of Canadians don't have access to palliative care, experts selected by the Royal Canadian Society say.
And, even though most Canadians want to die at home, 68.6 percent of them end up dying in the hospital.
Overall, the highest rate in this regard is recorded by Québec, where 86% of deaths occur in the hospital.
With regard to the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report reached conclusions that do not coincide with the position of the Federal Government, which has already stated that it does not wish to amend the Criminal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or do not constitute a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not led to an abuse of its application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or assisted suicide with non-competent persons or who have not given their consent.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, said yesterday by teleconference that, on the contrary, there were more excesses in those countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide have not been legalized.
"Ethanasia is practiced in Canada, although it is clearly illegal."
"In Canada, assisted suicide is practised, although it is clearly illegal," explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians, in favour of euthanasia
