Energy policy:
Facts must be worth more than dogmas
If there is one issue that cannot be addressed taking into account short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of enterprises.
It is fitting that an election meeting is time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will be useful only if it explores the set of economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic developments will mean doubling electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge part of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the growing shortage of fossil resources will have to be alleviated to continue to produce electricity continuously, not forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear power.
This is not the case either of Belgium, which subjects its own to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, or Switzerland, which is only aimed at building state-of-the-art power stations.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few examples, are moving forward with determination with their projects.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of an interrupted power plant after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, based on renewable energy, is sometimes presented as an example, reality goes against such a speech.
The Berlin election is going to mean an increase in the price of electricity, greater energy dependence due to the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be noticed.
The case of Denmark should be thought.
Champion of Europe in the wind sector, from which 30% of its electricity is also one of the large users of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbours pay an electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining industrial utility on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For this reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would mean a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would undermine the wonderful declarations on the reindustrialisation of our country and the defence of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French refuse to pay and, in fact, do not express opposition in principle to this type of energy, according to polls.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has lost construction of an industrial sector with 125,000 manufacturing jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it covers a galaxy of SMEs specializing in international markets and can create non-offshortenable jobs.
If France were to decide to abandon nuclear energy, it would mean the slaughter of a large part of these SMEs and the loss of the 6 billion euros per year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrician would command an EPR designed to run sixty years, when the collapse of its manufacturer is planned?
To solve the nuclear energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no diabolical source either.
Areva's development of low-carbon nuclear and renewable CO2 solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises strict and transparent control over existing plants and on the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of renowned professionalism, are also obsessed with security.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, that of Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it did not cause consequences for people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the design of the reactor and unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two unprecedented natural disasters, which resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as it did of the previous two.
Thanks to this progress and cooperation between the security authorities, and the French and German operators and builders, the RPA presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
As it is studied by all the electric players who want to build a plant, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for competitors of Areva and EDF, as it would leave them free to assume the leadership in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let excitement, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
Nicolas Sarkozy's immigration policy has been criticized from various points of view: the saturation of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with France's self-proclaimed "human rights country" status.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has made headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see the newspaper Libération of 23 May) proclaiming in the past that France "does not need foreign talents, workers or waiters."
However, it is rarely discussed economically.
The point is that, on this issue, there is quite a bit of consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the guidance by declaring in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country that has about two million immigrant workers," while on the left, the tone was set by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take care of all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of the invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In his program, Francois Hollande merely includes banalities, indicating that co-development will make it possible to solve the "immigration problem."
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, is perhaps profitable electorally, but economically it comes out very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work summarizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
The cap on immigration weakens growth and harms employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, particularly low-skilled workers, pushing for lower wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are rather complementary than substitutes for national workers and mainly employs in sectors with a lack of employment.
Poorly qualified immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country that lacks anesthetists, complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the latter to positively influence the wages and employment of nationals.
In view of the above, Giovanni Peri estimated that a 1% increase in migratory flows represents an increase in long-term real wages of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, without taking into account the fact that the diversity that immigrants bring contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel laureates and companies such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, as they contribute on average 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income less expenditure) of 150,000 euros to the public budgets on average throughout his life.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go and look for the points of growth that he lacked "with his teeth."
These teeth, which deterred immigrants, had exactly the reverse effect.
