From Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris worries about links between Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
Links between the terrorist group Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect of Boko Haram, suspected for a long time, have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel even said Algiers already "has certainty."
"The way both organizations operate and intelligence reports show that they are cooperating," he explained, without providing further details.
Paris seems to come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the abduction of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have resumed the catwalks.
Raped in a Niamey restaurant by people related to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the next day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators discovered several phone chips belonging to the terrorists.
Terrorist Axis
The study of the calls made indicates several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers especially captured the researchers' interest: one leads to a long-time Nigerian who remained in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who is supposedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
"This is progress, but we certainly have to wait to have more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram."
"But it's possible".
"We have known for years that the sect has enjoyed external financial and intellectual support and is becoming increasingly active," says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, these "supports" had proved increasingly evident in the evolution and discourses of Boko Haram or in its operational modes, which now involve the use of increasingly complex kamikazes or explosive devices and in the same style as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has since been pressing Abuya to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities, in fact, have long considered the group as a community of enlightened uninterested.
A quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (meaning, in hausa, "Western education is a sin"), it incites the establishment of an Islamic emirate in Nigeria's Muslim north.
In this poor region, the association is experiencing a rapid success.
It is politicized and demanded strict respect for sharia law, while its militants are thrown into the fight against the ungodly central government.
The latter are first oriented towards churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were particularly active and attacks on police stations multiplied.
Abuya's reaction was, as is often widespread.
The army attacked the city and 800 people were killed.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested in life, is killed in prison.
Since then, the sect has become radicalized and abandons its fiefdoms from the north.
Last Christmas, he claims an attack that causes 80 deaths in Jos and then another in Abuya.
In June, Boko Haram again attacked Abuya, particularly the police guarded headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first of its kind.
In August, the United Nations headquarters became its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, ranging from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria, is of the concern to all security specialists.
While Aqmi has attacked Mali and Niger and the Somalis of Al-Chebab operating in Kenya, Boko Haram emerges as a new threat in the center of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with Goodluck Jonathan President Alain Juppé warned him against Boko Haram and said he was willing to "share all the information."
