Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe with Russia through the Baltic Sea fund, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, at the inauguration of Nord Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister Francois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart, Mark Rutte, have turned together the steering wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe through a first had 1,224 km that connect the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be completed by the end of 2012 which will allow the supply of a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, i.e. enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time of this huge work presents airs of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding the ground run by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
At the sudden, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be harder to influence Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact," referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of the energy Europe, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has been able, in just five years, to triumph its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically," Francois Fillon confirmed during the inauguration of the pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which the big contracts in the gas sector are as political as they are economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the directors of Gazprom, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The underwater tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect against the anchors of ships.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m deep.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution," says Jens Moller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in its entirety: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Sweden's waters, but project officials gave it up to see that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state-owned society to establish itself permanently at sea off its coasts.
"In case of a breakdown, we will interrupt the passage of the gas in less than a minute," says Jens Moller.
In the event of leakage, the gas pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But builders consider it unlikely that a leak will occur, as they have forecast joints that are expected to have a leak every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, which carries out external inspections, as well as through a device circulating inside the pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is inserted inside the tube, which has a diameter of one metre, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides precise data on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline has been designed to run for fifty years without any repair.
The circulation of the gas is guaranteed simply by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by the Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream, in charge of building and operating the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zoug, Switzerland, where the imposition is particularly favourable.
Afterwards, Gazprom rented to the company, for a period of twenty-five renewable years, all gas transport capacities.
"Gazprom will be paid for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually transported," says Jens Moller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline has been completed by 30% with the contribution of shareholders and 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach EUR 7.4 billion for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom alone assumes the risk of expenses.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy pine-polted coast.
Valve, 4.5 meters high, form the gas exit door.
There are sensors that measure the specific pressure, temperature and characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has received a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At total capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a branded notebook.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people back taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as once aging by time.
However, the Moleskine notebooks with the current look were born in 1997.
The Italian company Mode Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a notebook of designer but distinguished notes.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant to the company, was in charge of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an old production technique, mole skin (to mole skin), which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the banquets.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to today's taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Mode Mode.
And it was successful.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26 per cent to a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the first years has been left, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond Italy's borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the profile of the buyer, since the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cult.
The small Italian company, which had 12 workers in its infancy, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops of the city center, and has been able to impose his identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural firm goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also released a notebook with leopard covers, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, schedules, pens, computer covers... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that provokes envy: in autumn 2006, Mode Mode was acquired by the SG Capital Europe investment fund, currently Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
About 19 per cent of disabled people are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a resolved public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people doubles the average rate: 19 per cent, compared with 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Dealer?
"No," says Eric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made for fifteen years is considerable.
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there is still a lot to do."
It should be mentioned that the disabled continue to face numerous obstacles to access employment.
They are often older: 37 per cent are over 50 (on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80 per cent have not finished baccalaureate and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38 per cent on average.
In other words, there are many issues that make it particularly difficult to return to the world of work and that "constitute the crux of the problem," says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those that are not mentioned; people's mentality advances, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association for the Cité noted that the directors surveyed have "a level of knowledge about low disabilities," with an "excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually deficient."
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the target of hiring 6% of disabled workers, a target set in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest figures available, dating back to 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6 per cent.
"We are now reaching around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The test: the number of establishments "subject to this contribution," as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (from 606 million to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has generated great pressure for companies," Pierre Blanc explains.
"But this improvement also reflects real awareness, particularly among the big groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of companies with between 20 and 49 workers have disabled employees on their workforce, compared with 82 per cent of companies with between 100 and 199 workers.
